crops.presented_by: Robert M. Grey, Superintendent, Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum, Soledad, Cienfuegos
crops.institution_involved: Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum
crops.description: ARIKURYROBA SCHIZOPHYLLA (Mart.) Bailey. Phoenicaceae. Palm. A small slender-stemmed palm, about 15 feet high, with pinnate leaves. Native to Brazil. For previous introduction see 104681. From Cuba. Seeds and plants presented by Robert M. Grey, Superintendent, Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum, Soledad, Cienfuegos. Received in May 1934.

crops.presented_by: Robert M. Grey, Superintendent, Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum, Soledad, Cienfuegos
crops.institution_involved: Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum
crops.description: BAUHINIA RACEMOSA Lam. Caesalpiniaceae. A small shrub with drooping branches and rounded leaves, the two lobes rounded oval, white-hairy beneath. The small yellow flowers are in racemes of 12 to 18. Native to eastern India. From Cuba. Seeds and plants presented by Robert M. Grey, Superintendent, Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum, Soledad, Cienfuegos. Received in May 1934.

crops.presented_by: Robert M. Grey, Superintendent, Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum, Soledad, Cienfuegos
crops.institution_involved: Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum
crops.description: LIVISTONA CHINENSIS (Jacq.) R. Br. Phoenicaceae. Palm. A palm, native to China, with a short thick trunk up to 6 feet high and 1 foot thick, having a crown of reniform palmately divided leaves 4 to 6 feet across on petioles about 5 feet long, which are armed below the middle with recurved brown spines more than an inch long. For previous introduction see 93412. From Cuba. Seeds and plants presented by Robert M. Grey, Superintendent, Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum, Soledad, Cienfuegos. Received in May 1934.

crops.presented_by: Robert M. Grey, Superintendent, Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum, Soledad, Cienfuegos
crops.institution_involved: Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum
crops.description: LIVISTONA COCHINCHINENSIS (Blume) Mart. Phoenicaceae. Palm. A slender palm about 50 feet high, with a crown of large fan-shaped leaves. It is native to Malacca. For previous introduction see 104240. From Cuba. Seeds and plants presented by Robert M. Grey, Superintendent, Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum, Soledad, Cienfuegos. Received in May 1934.

crops.description: ADENIUM OBESUM (Forsk.) Roem. and Schult. Apocynaceae. For previous introduction and description see 105448. From Cuba. Seeds and plants presented by Robert M. Grey, Superintendent, Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum, Soledad, Cienfuegos. Received in May 1934.

DOLICHANDRONE CRISPA Seem. Bignoniaceae. A large tropical tree, 40 to 60 feet high, with compound leaves a foot or less in length, the two to four broadly elliptic leaves being 2 to 4 inches long. The white flowers are in small corymbs. Native to southern India.

FAGRAEA OBOVATA Wall. Plants of a tropical tree of moderate size, with ovate or rounded thick leaves 5 or 6 inches long and fragrant white flowers 2 inches long, in corymblike clusters. Native to Assam, India.
LONCHOCARPUS NEUROSCAPHA Benth. Lancepod. An evergreen tree with alternate pinnate leaves and racemes of purplish pea-like flowers. For previous introduction see 94776.

crops.origin: Central Mercedita, Pinar del Rio, Cuba; species native to the East Indies
crops.presented_by: Presented through W. A. Mace, Madruga, Cuba, and L. H. Dewey, Bureau of Plant Industry
crops.description: ARTOCARPUS COMMUNIS Forst. Breadnut. From Central Mercedita, Pinar del Rio, Cuba. Seeds presented through W. A. Mace, Madruga, Cuba, and L. H. Dewey, Bureau of Plant Industry. Received June 1, 1934. A tree, native to the East Indies, 30 to 40 feet high, with viscid milky juice and leathery ovate leaves 3 feet long, entire at the base but divided above into 3 to 9 lobes. The large fruits, 4 to 6 inches in diameter, are often seedless, but in this variety the seeds are present and are much the size, shape, and flavor of chestnuts. For previous introduction see 80173.

crops.presented_by: Julius Matz
crops.description: OLEA EUROPAEA L. Oleaceae. Common olive. From Spain. Cuttings presented by Julius Matz, Bureau of Plant Industry. Received June 25, 1934. Variety Zorzalena. A relatively tender variety. The tree is leafy, compact, and a good early bearer whose fruit is grown for its oil.

crops.presented_by: Presented through David Fairchild, Bureau of Plant Industry
crops.description: CAVANILLESIA PLATANIFOLIA H. B. K. Bombacaceae. From the Canal Zone. Seeds presented through David Fairchild, Bureau of Plant Industry. Received May 28, 1934. A Colombian tree up to 100 feet high with a large thick trunk, smooth pale bark, large shallowly five- to seven-lobed leaves, and red flowers 1 inch long. The soft coarse pithlike wood is white or yellowish and is used for making canoes and rafts. For previous introduction see 98928.
